crops.institution_involved: State Board of Agriculture of South Dakota
crops.description: Variety Honey, introduced from Bulgaria. Supplied as 16 1-ounce packages. Evaluated by Mr. H. C. Warner of the State Board of Agriculture of South Dakota, who tested it alongside Connectient, Field, Potiron, Etampes, Tours, Large Cheese, Japanese, Cushow, Black Sugar, Gray Bologne, and Pie; while some comparators were more productive, this variety led in quality. Recommended for wide distribution for culinary use and for feeding milch cows. Reported success on rich, sandy loam; vines endured drought; fruit ripened by the beginning of September. Similar excellence was not observed in California.

Variety Kochanka, a Russian type. Supplied as 27 packages. Oval fruit with green flesh; very productive; medium early; sweet and juicy. Extensively used for confectionery, cooked in sugar by a distinctive process.
Russian variety from Belbek, Crimea. Supplied as 38 packages. Oblong fruit, dark green rind; bright red flesh; early.
Variety Empress of Melons, a Russian type. Supplied as 57 packages. Oval fruit with variegated surface; green flesh that is delicate, melting, and very sweet; extremely early and highly productive.
Supplied as 42 packages. Dark green rind with red flesh; moderately late.

crops.origin: Russia (originally from Lenkoran, Province of Baku, Transcaucasia)
crops.description: Variety Lenkoran No. 2. Supplied as 227 packages. Oval shape; exterior bright yellow with small dark spots; green flesh; ripens late and keeps well.
Variety Favorite of the Pjatigorsk farm, a Russian type, obtained directly from its native locality. Supplied as 26 packages. Round fruit; green rind with dark stripes; orange flesh; very early.
Variety General Skobeleff II, an Asiatic type introduced into Russia from Khiva, Turkestan. Supplied as 31 packages. Round fruit; white rind; orange flesh; medium early.
Variety The Czar of Baktcha, a Russian type. Supplied as 22 packages. Very large fruit; bright green rind with dark stripes; red flesh; rather late.

Variety Favorite of the Pjatigorsk farm, a Russian type. Supplied as 20 packages. Round fruit; green rind with dark stripes; dark red flesh; very early; described as magnificent. Evidently the same as No. 20.
Variety Jea Teveam, originally from China. Supplied as 34 packages. Blackish green rind; rose-colored flesh; moderately late.
